{
  "answer": "Soul and Body II (unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e, ch. 10): The soul is the speaker, returning every seven nights to condemn the damned body. The most uncomfortable line for the soul if addressed back to it is the poem's own climactic admission: 'But what shall we two do, when He has joined us again a second time? Then we must together forever endure such miseries as you prescribed for us.' (p-7f7247) The soul pours out righteous rage against the body — 'you bound me with hard hunger and fettered me with the torments of hell' — but cannot escape the logic of shared damnation: at the resurrection, soul and body will be reunited and condemned together. The soul is just as accountable as the body. What this tradition is most worried about at the moment of judgment is bodily indulgence displacing the soul's longing for God ('you were proud with your feasting, sated with wine, you swelled with splendor, while I was athirst for God's body') — and the resulting impossibility of any defense before the Lord on Doomsday.\n\nSmriti tradition — Āṅgirasa Smṛti (unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1, ch. 1, Ang_2,6.7, p-1de5ee): 'The Guru is the chastiser of the self-controlled; the king is the chastiser of the wicked. The chastiser of those with hidden sins is Yama, the son of Vivasvat.' This is the line the tradition (as speaker/authority) would least like addressed back to it: the principle of a judge who sees all hidden sins implies that no judge — not even Yama — is exempt from a higher cosmic accounting. The complementary verse (Ang_2,6.8, p-93d7c1) makes this explicit: 'The Guru, the king, or Yama, when he chastises according to dharma, is freed from sin; the chastised one attains good, being struck by fear.' Yama's freedom from sin depends on his chastising correctly — leaving open the dread of misjudgment. What the smriti tradition is most worried about at the moment of judgment is hidden sin: sins that escaped the guru and the king can never escape Yama. The terror is not public wickedness (which the king handles) but the secret interior life — concealed transgressions that no human court saw but that Yama's record registers exactly, as calibrated and inescapable as the verse in the same text: 'For however many morsels of the oblation that lowly one eats, so many spikes he swallows upon reaching Yama, the son of Vivasvat.' (Ang_1.739, p-3c396a)",
